        "range": "21:1-3",
        "excerpt": "When the Canaanite, the king of Arad, who lived in the Negev, heard that Israel was coming by the way of Atharim, then he fought against Israel and took some of them captive.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a battle and ends with two more. Arad is in the northern Negev, on the southern approach to Canaan from Kadesh. The king of Arad's preemptive attack — taking some Israelites captive — provokes Israel's first recorded vow of devoted destruction (*charam*, the same root as the place-name Hormah). Israel does not strike out in their own strength; they make a conditional vow: *if You will indeed deliver this people into my hand, then I will utterly destroy their cities.* The vow is right-shaped — dependence first, action second. Yahweh hears, delivers, and Israel performs the vow.\n\nThe geographical and verbal detail is loaded. *Hormah* appears earlier in Numbers 14:45 — the place where the wilderness generation, after refusing to enter at Kadesh-barnea, then presumptuously attacked and was routed by 'the Amalekites and the Canaanites who lived in that hill country, and they struck them and beat them down as far as Hormah.' The same site, the same name, now becomes the site of Israel's first victory. The reversal is intentional: where the old generation was 'devoted to destruction' for its rebellion, the new generation now 'devotes' its enemies to destruction in obedience to a vow rightly made.\n\nThe theological note is foundational for the chapter: Israel's military success is conditioned on covenant dependence. They do not vow without Yahweh's hearing; they do not strike without His delivering. The verbs of vv. 2-3 are precisely calibrated — Israel *vows*, Yahweh *hears* and *delivers*, then Israel *destroys*. Conquest is never autonomous; it is response.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Charam* (חרם) is the verb of holy war — to devote something irrevocably to Yahweh, whether by destruction (as here) or by setting apart for sacred use. The noun *cherem* (devoted thing) describes the spoils that may not be appropriated. Hormah (חָרְמָה) is the same root nominalized as place-name. The wordplay between act and place is built into Hebrew."
