        "number": 3,
        "title": "The well-song and the itinerary of approach",
        "range": "21:10-20",
        "excerpt": "Spring up, O well! Sing to it! The well, which the leaders sank, which the nobles of the people dug, with the scepter and with their staffs.",
        "body": "After the serpent-and-bronze, the chapter shifts to an itinerary section (vv. 10-20). Eleven place names mark Israel's accelerating march around Moab toward the Amorite frontier. This is not random; it is the deliberate narrowing of geography toward the Jordan crossing. Each stage takes Israel from Oboth (south of the Dead Sea) up the eastern flank of Moab, across the Arnon gorge, and to the heights of Pisgah — the very mountain where Moses will eventually die looking into the land (Deuteronomy 34:1).\n\nTwo poetic fragments interrupt the itinerary. The first (vv. 14-15) is the narrator's citation from 'the Book of the Wars of the LORD' — a now-lost compilation of Israel's military poetry, mentioned only here in the canon. The citation is fragmentary, listing place names along the Arnon, signaling that Israel's journey is *that kind* of event — written in Yahweh's war-annals. The very existence of such a book is theologically suggestive: Israel's wars are not their own; they belong in Yahweh's archive.\n\nThe second poetic fragment (vv. 17-18) is the well-song itself — one of only two Israelite songs in the wilderness era (Exodus 15 being the other). 'Spring up, O well! Sing to it!' This is sung *response* to Yahweh's gift of water at Beer (v. 16). And the contrast with v. 5 is the chapter's pastoral pivot. Both episodes involve Israel needing water in the wilderness. In v. 5, the need produced contempt: 'we loathe this miserable food.' In v. 17, the same need (now answered by Yahweh's free word — 'Assemble the people, that I may give them water,' v. 16) produces *song*. The difference is not the circumstance; it is the heart's posture toward the Giver.\n\nThere is also a strikingly democratic note in the song: 'the well which the leaders sank, which the nobles of the people dug, with the scepter and with their staffs.' The new generation is led by a different kind of leadership — leaders who *dig* with the people, not who strike rocks in anger (cf. Moses' disqualifying act in 20:10-12). The well-song is, in miniature, a foretaste of how the new generation will live in the land — sustained by Yahweh's gift, shepherded by leaders who serve.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Beer* (בְּאֵר) — well — gives the place-name (v. 16) and is repeated in the song; the play is between the geographical site and the gift. The well-song's brevity and parallelism mark it as ancient lyric, possibly older than its surrounding prose, lending the narrative archaeological gravity."
