        "number": 5,
        "title": "Og of Bashan — the giant falls and the inheritance is doubled",
        "range": "21:33-35",
        "excerpt": "But the LORD said to Moses, 'Do not fear him, for I have given him into your hand, and all his people and his land; and you shall do to him as you did to Sihon, king of the Amorites, who lived at Heshbon.'",
        "body": "The chapter closes with the conquest of Og, king of Bashan — three verses that change Israel's geopolitical situation. Bashan is the fertile plateau north of the Jabbok, famous in later Scripture for its 'bulls of Bashan' (Psalm 22:12) and 'oaks of Bashan' (Isaiah 2:13) — a region of agricultural and military prestige. Og himself is later described as the last of the Rephaim, the giants of pre-conquest Canaan, with a bed thirteen feet long (Deuteronomy 3:11). For the new generation, Og represents exactly what the previous generation had feared in the spies' report — 'the giants… and we were like grasshoppers in our own sight' (Numbers 13:33).\n\nThe theological force is concentrated in v. 34: 'Do not fear him, for I have given him into your hand.' This is the inverse of Kadesh-barnea. There the old generation, seeing the same kind of giant inhabitants, said, 'we are not able to go up against the people, for they are too strong for us' (13:31). Here, before the new generation can even formulate the same fear, Yahweh preempts it: *do not fear*. The verb tense matters — 'I *have given*' (Hebrew perfect, signaling completed action from God's standpoint) — the victory is accomplished in the divine economy before the battle begins. Faith's task is to act on what God has already done.\n\nThe outcome (v. 35) is total: 'they killed him and his sons and all his people, until there was no remnant left him; and they possessed his land.' The threefold completeness — Og, his sons, his people — and the language of *yarash* (possessing) echo the conquest formulas that will fill Joshua. Numbers 21 is, in this final pericope, the proleptic Joshua — the conquest in miniature, east of the Jordan, anticipating the conquest west of the Jordan.\n\nThe chapter therefore ends with Israel dwelling in two former kingdoms — Sihon's Amorite territory and Og's Bashan — territories that will become the inheritance of Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh (Numbers 32; Joshua 13). The wandering is functionally over. The new generation, still rebellious (21:5), still bitten (21:6), still saved by looking (21:9), now stands at the threshold of the rest of the inheritance with their first two giant-kings defeated and their land possessed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yare* (fear) in 'do not fear him' (v. 34) is the verb of paralyzing dread, not reverent awe. The cognate noun *yir'ah* can mean either, but the imperative *al tira* ('do not fear') is the standard divine reassurance formula (Genesis 15:1; 26:24; Joshua 1:9; Isaiah 41:10) — the word with which Yahweh repeatedly grounds courage in His preceding promise rather than the believer's strength."
